00:02:47,228 --> 00:02:49,008
and by showing you the Stone Mason level,

63
00:02:49,088 --> 00:02:50,749
I can sort of use it as a microcosm

64
00:02:51,149 --> 00:02:52,609
for the level design of the game itself.

65
00:02:53,516 --> 00:02:55,097
So we'll check back on this every now and then.

66
00:02:55,117 --> 00:02:57,178
It's sort of the anchor to the presentation.

67
00:02:57,198 --> 00:02:58,840
And then we'll go into the level.

68
00:02:58,880 --> 00:03:01,361
I'll show you how the level rules work out in practice.

69
00:03:01,641 --> 00:03:03,222
And I'll show you some of the beats leading up to level.

70
00:03:03,262 --> 00:03:05,604
And you'll kind of get how the overall flow packages up

71
00:03:05,644 --> 00:03:06,325
from level to level.

72
00:03:06,827 --> 00:03:08,728
So to get us started, here's our first rule.

73
00:03:08,748 --> 00:03:10,570
It's all about core pillars.

74
00:03:11,770 --> 00:03:13,732
Sometimes a contentious topic in game design.

75
00:03:13,772 --> 00:03:15,893
Some people really like to use core pillars, some people don't.

76
00:03:16,373 --> 00:03:16,914
I think they're great.

77
00:03:18,034 --> 00:03:20,356
I like core pillars because they let us know what to focus on.

78
00:03:20,456 --> 00:03:22,657
You could sort of think of them maybe as a lens of focus

79
00:03:22,677 --> 00:03:24,439
that help us to all start getting thinking

80
00:03:24,859 --> 00:03:26,000
in the same direction together.

81
00:03:27,369 --> 00:03:29,912
And we can't do everything in every game ever,

82
00:03:29,952 --> 00:03:31,333
nor do we really want to, right?

83
00:03:31,373 --> 00:03:34,195
Because if we do things with a bit of focus,

84
00:03:34,295 --> 00:03:36,818
what we'll hopefully end up with is a few things

85
00:03:36,998 --> 00:03:38,319
that make the game really special,

86
00:03:38,479 --> 00:03:40,081
something that actually helps to separate it

87
00:03:40,201 --> 00:03:41,782
from every other game out there.

88
00:03:42,363 --> 00:03:43,744
And so you can think of the core pillars

89
00:03:43,844 --> 00:03:45,045
as creative building blocks.

90
00:03:45,485 --> 00:03:46,726
And as we step through this talk,

91
00:03:46,766 --> 00:03:48,348
I'll be going over core pillars a lot.

92
00:03:49,068 --> 00:03:51,589
But before we do, here's a quick history lesson.

93
00:03:52,129 --> 00:03:55,751
God of War 1, 2, 3, and Ascension, the PSP versions,

94
00:03:56,151 --> 00:03:59,392
they all have core pillars that focus on a few key areas

95
00:03:59,452 --> 00:03:59,812
as well.

96
00:03:59,932 --> 00:04:03,033
You might describe them as combat, platforming,

97
00:04:03,253 --> 00:04:03,833
and puzzles.

98
00:04:04,333 --> 00:04:06,354
And as you probably remember, God of War

99
00:04:06,374 --> 00:04:07,774
was actually a game with a rail camera.

100
00:04:08,495 --> 00:04:13,518
So it was often seen as this best-in-class bombastic action game, action adventure game.

101
00:04:13,979 --> 00:04:19,463
But by 2014, there was a very strong feeling both inside the studio and outside the studio

102
00:04:19,483 --> 00:04:23,346
that we needed to start looking at these core pillars and the anatomy that really makes

103
00:04:23,426 --> 00:04:24,506
up the game itself.

104
00:04:25,830 --> 00:04:27,711
Now, for a franchise to switch up its core pillars

105
00:04:27,771 --> 00:04:29,873
is not the type of thing you want to do all the time, right?

106
00:04:30,254 --> 00:04:32,316
Because what you're actually going to start to look at is,

107
00:04:32,836 --> 00:04:34,177
are we reevaluating the things

108
00:04:34,197 --> 00:04:35,959
that players find most fun about this game?

109
00:04:36,259 --> 00:04:38,221
We're going to actually start unpackaging that.

110
00:04:38,241 --> 00:04:40,243
We're going to take all the pieces of the engine,

111
00:04:40,283 --> 00:04:42,465
spread them out on the floor, and see how they all fit together.

112
00:04:43,125 --> 00:04:45,407
So, with that in mind, Cory Barlog, our creative director,

113
00:04:45,427 --> 00:04:48,130
and a few key team members sort of siphoned themselves off

114
00:04:48,170 --> 00:04:48,750
for a little while,

115
00:04:49,991 --> 00:04:52,674
and they had the goal of creating a new set of pillars.

116
00:04:54,237 --> 00:04:56,600
The three pillars that they came up with,

117
00:04:56,640 --> 00:04:58,102
and I won't step you through the full process

118
00:04:58,122 --> 00:04:59,124
of how this was generated,

119
00:04:59,664 --> 00:05:00,806
but they were very successful,

120
00:05:00,866 --> 00:05:04,031
were combat, narrative, and exploration.

121
00:05:05,552 --> 00:05:08,134
And for level design, this is a very big change.

122
00:05:08,855 --> 00:05:09,295
It's great.

123
00:05:09,455 --> 00:05:11,837
It starts to give us a lot of things to start focusing on.

124
00:05:12,277 --> 00:05:14,979
But it actually also starts tapping into a lot of things

125
00:05:14,999 --> 00:05:17,781
that we sort of lack expertise in at Santa Monica Studio.

126
00:05:18,501 --> 00:05:21,443
But it's a good opportunity to start thinking in new terms

127
00:05:21,523 --> 00:05:23,604
and how we take on modern design challenges.

128
00:05:23,805 --> 00:05:25,306
We can't keep doing the same thing forever,

129
00:05:25,326 --> 00:05:27,947
so how do we start thinking with a new lens of focus?

130
00:05:28,648 --> 00:05:33,012
You can start asking yourself, all right, well, what would Combat 2.0 even mean?

131
00:05:33,332 --> 00:05:35,875
How does this work with a new camera? How do encounters work?

132
00:05:36,335 --> 00:05:37,537
How do we build fight spaces?

133
00:05:38,638 --> 00:05:41,500
Sure, a lot of people say they want to be a modern narrative game,

134
00:05:41,721 --> 00:05:42,882
but what does that even mean?

135
00:05:43,102 --> 00:05:47,286
How do you tell stories? What are the components that come together to make that happen?

136
00:05:48,327 --> 00:05:51,770
And a lot of people think of exploration just in terms of larger spaces.

137
00:05:51,950 --> 00:05:54,253
But how big is too big? How wide is too wide?

138
00:05:54,293 --> 00:05:57,316
What do you even do other than just exploring or roaming?

139
00:05:57,876 --> 00:06:00,619
And of course, at the center of all of this, you have Kratos and Atreus,

140
00:06:00,959 --> 00:06:02,881
you know, trying to tell a father-son story.

141
00:06:02,901 --> 00:06:06,064
So you're trying to take combat, narrative, and exploration

142
00:06:06,284 --> 00:06:08,927
as your first pillars of focus.

143
00:06:09,127 --> 00:06:10,628
And at the center of it, you're trying to think of

144
00:06:10,969 --> 00:06:13,251
how this will all tie into a father-son story.

145
00:06:14,403 --> 00:06:16,245
Here's a quick version of Vision Book.

146
00:06:16,325 --> 00:06:17,967
This is the one that Corey put together.

147
00:06:18,227 --> 00:06:19,148
I think it was fabulous.

148
00:06:19,228 --> 00:06:21,611
In fact, you can see all through the book

149
00:06:21,651 --> 00:06:23,513
that combat narrative and exploration

150
00:06:23,533 --> 00:06:25,034
are very heavily represented.

151
00:06:25,615 --> 00:06:28,698
In fact, Corey believed so strongly at these three pillars

152
00:06:28,718 --> 00:06:31,400
that you pretty much can't get a cup of coffee at the studio

153
00:06:31,460 --> 00:06:32,922
without having to look at it, which

154
00:06:32,982 --> 00:06:36,125
is a particularly good way to start brainwashing everyone.

155
00:06:39,280 --> 00:06:41,481
And I know this is something that designers really respected.

156
00:06:41,541 --> 00:06:43,481
The fact that Corey stayed to these three pillars

157
00:06:43,561 --> 00:06:45,822
gave us some really strong anchors through the project

158
00:06:45,982 --> 00:06:46,782
that we could work on.

159
00:06:47,922 --> 00:06:49,603
So, with these three pillars in mind,

160
00:06:49,663 --> 00:06:50,963
as I step through the presentation,

161
00:06:51,003 --> 00:06:53,564
start to try to think about combat, narrative,

162
00:06:53,604 --> 00:06:54,864
and exploration a lot.

163
00:06:55,924 --> 00:06:58,465
This stonemason level did take a long time to put together.

164
00:06:58,665 --> 00:07:02,506
You know, we spent a long time tuning it and iterating on it,

165
00:07:02,606 --> 00:07:04,786
even with these great pillars that we could focus on.

166
00:07:05,723 --> 00:07:07,264
But the thing that's great about this level

167
00:07:07,304 --> 00:07:08,285
is when it came together,

168
00:07:08,325 --> 00:07:10,866
it sort of became a fully architected expression

169
00:07:10,906 --> 00:07:13,167
that delivered on combat narrative and exploration.

170
00:07:13,987 --> 00:07:15,708
And most importantly, it proved to us

171
00:07:15,788 --> 00:07:18,069
that if you distribute those three pillars correctly,

172
00:07:18,489 --> 00:07:20,810
you can actually deliver on the variety of pacing

173
00:07:21,450 --> 00:07:22,750
that we're looking to master.

174
00:07:23,011 --> 00:07:25,532
Not just an action game and not just an adventure game,

175
00:07:25,572 --> 00:07:28,013
but a real mix of action and adventure, right?

176
00:07:28,913 --> 00:07:31,274
So let's take a look with a bit of a deeper dive

177
00:07:31,354 --> 00:07:32,835
how the game and how the level

178
00:07:32,875 --> 00:07:33,955
delivers on those three pillars.

179
00:07:34,695 --> 00:07:36,376
I'll start with the most obvious one, combat.

180
00:07:37,217 --> 00:07:38,918
Well, this, of course, details everything

181
00:07:38,938 --> 00:07:41,340
that is the most action-focused component of the game.

182
00:07:41,420 --> 00:07:43,081
It's the capital A in action adventure.

183
00:07:43,962 --> 00:07:46,343
And it's everything from Kratos' core attack loop

184
00:07:46,464 --> 00:07:49,065
to the AI he faces, the upgrades that can be achieved,

185
00:07:49,146 --> 00:07:51,968
and perhaps most importantly, how a support character

186
00:07:51,988 --> 00:07:53,729
like Atreus might contribute to that fight.

187
00:07:54,975 --> 00:07:57,136
You can see here inside the category of combat,

188
00:07:57,156 --> 00:07:58,677
there's actually a lot of sub-archetypes.

189
00:07:59,117 --> 00:08:01,278
It's not just arenas or fight spaces.

190
00:08:01,798 --> 00:08:03,919
There's also sort of more wide linear scenarios

191
00:08:03,939 --> 00:08:06,641
where you can take on the AI in more free-form ways.

192
00:08:07,181 --> 00:08:08,281
Down the bottom on the left there,

193
00:08:08,301 --> 00:08:10,402
you'll see what I call a special rules scenario.

194
00:08:10,442 --> 00:08:12,503
This one has a timer that sort of gets the variety

195
00:08:12,543 --> 00:08:13,684
a bit different from everything else.

196
00:08:14,084 --> 00:08:15,165
Of course, you have boss battles,

197
00:08:15,185 --> 00:08:16,445
you have lots of different things

198
00:08:17,025 --> 00:08:18,806
that come together to just make combat

199
00:08:18,926 --> 00:08:20,807
more than just fights, right?

200
00:08:21,931 --> 00:08:23,352
So the core pillar of combat is great.

201
00:08:23,693 --> 00:08:26,155
It gives us a lot that we can start thinking about early on,

202
00:08:26,756 --> 00:08:29,419
but what's really good about it is it has enough versatility

203
00:08:29,579 --> 00:08:31,821
that we can start to create sub-archetypes inside it.

204
00:08:32,542 --> 00:08:33,963
It's a great place for level designers

205
00:08:33,983 --> 00:08:35,064
to start to put their focus,

206
00:08:35,605 --> 00:08:37,146
and if you look at the Mason level here,

207
00:08:37,166 --> 00:08:38,808
you'll see that it's pretty heavily distributed

208
00:08:38,828 --> 00:08:40,750
throughout the level, exactly what you'd expect.

209
00:08:41,090 --> 00:08:42,832
There's a lot of different fights that take place,

210
00:08:42,912 --> 00:08:43,993
and they're paced out really well.

211
00:08:45,731 --> 00:08:47,492
Secondly, narrative.

212
00:08:48,192 --> 00:08:50,273
Well, you might not expect that out of a God of War game,

213
00:08:50,313 --> 00:08:51,873
especially with the history of the franchise.

214
00:08:51,893 --> 00:08:54,274
God of War has actually always had a strong narrative

215
00:08:54,294 --> 00:08:57,095
through it, but it's never really been narrative gameplay.

216
00:08:57,596 --> 00:08:59,096
So what we can start thinking about now

217
00:08:59,176 --> 00:09:01,457
is what is the father-son adventure

218
00:09:01,477 --> 00:09:03,578
that Kratos and Atreus are actually going to go on?

219
00:09:04,278 --> 00:09:04,418
It's

220
00:09:05,275 --> 00:09:08,357
The tone, it's the level's purpose, it's the overall lore.

221
00:09:08,777 --> 00:09:12,079
A good level has a story and has an adventure behind it, right?

222
00:09:12,099 --> 00:09:14,360
So we can actually start thinking about how to deliver on that.

223
00:09:15,060 --> 00:09:19,342
Again, there's a few sub-archetypes of narrative gameplay that we can look into.

224
00:09:20,443 --> 00:09:23,424
You've got cut scenes, of course, but we tried to innovate on this

225
00:09:23,484 --> 00:09:25,345
by having no camera cuts throughout these.

226
00:09:26,085 --> 00:09:28,166
You can see there's sort of more slow-paced sections

227
00:09:28,206 --> 00:09:30,928
where Kratos and Atreus can have conversations with one another.

228
00:09:31,740 --> 00:09:35,504
Down the bottom, a lot of games are starting to become masters

229
00:09:35,544 --> 00:09:37,366
of this right now, environmental storytelling.

230
00:09:37,447 --> 00:09:39,489
How do we give the environment a sense of place?

231
00:09:39,529 --> 00:09:41,071
How do we tie it into the overall law?

232
00:09:41,732 --> 00:09:43,674
And of course, you can see on the bottom right,

233
00:09:43,774 --> 00:09:45,476
even Atreus has little animations

234
00:09:45,516 --> 00:09:48,039
that we put in the levels to try and emphasize

235
00:09:48,159 --> 00:09:50,642
and accentuate his state of mind.

236
00:09:51,453 --> 00:09:53,755
There's even little secrets that allow the player to find lore.

237
00:09:53,775 --> 00:09:56,977
There's a lot of different categories inside that core pillar of narrative,

238
00:09:57,077 --> 00:09:57,718
and that's great.

239
00:09:58,158 --> 00:10:01,020
Again, like combat, it gives us a lot of different versatility

240
00:10:01,040 --> 00:10:02,901
and variety that we can create inside the level.

241
00:10:03,942 --> 00:10:05,543
If you look at it from the top-down perspective,

242
00:10:05,563 --> 00:10:08,486
you might even be surprised how much narrative is inside this level.

243
00:10:08,866 --> 00:10:11,348
And that doesn't even include the fact that you're in a level

244
00:10:11,428 --> 00:10:13,890
with a giant, interesting-looking fallen giant, right?

245
00:10:15,017 --> 00:10:18,178
So once again, you can see we're able to get a lot of variety

246
00:10:18,398 --> 00:10:21,459
and density out of that sort of initial pillar of narrative.

247
00:10:22,679 --> 00:10:25,060
And rounding out the three pillars is exploration.

248
00:10:25,220 --> 00:10:26,361
And this is what I would consider

249
00:10:26,381 --> 00:10:28,401
to be the most complicated of the three pillars.

250
00:10:29,253 --> 00:10:31,314
The pillar of exploration is great.

251
00:10:31,534 --> 00:10:34,276
It represents the desire for larger layouts, sure.

252
00:10:34,737 --> 00:10:37,258
It represents the desire for more wide linear spaces,

253
00:10:37,478 --> 00:10:37,939
of course.

254
00:10:38,559 --> 00:10:42,362
But it also represents the design shift in the camera.

255
00:10:42,542 --> 00:10:44,583
The fact that you can actually move the camera around now

256
00:10:44,623 --> 00:10:46,905
means every space is more explorable than before.

257
00:10:47,565 --> 00:10:50,729
There's a famous phrase taught to me earlier in my career

258
00:10:50,749 --> 00:10:53,212
by Morgan Jaffa, which is, camera is genre.

259
00:10:53,512 --> 00:10:56,696
Where you place the camera is possibly what type of game

260
00:10:56,716 --> 00:10:57,297
you are making.

261
00:10:58,038 --> 00:11:00,420
And when we shift the camera from a real camera game

262
00:11:00,781 --> 00:11:05,346
to a fully 3D game, now we have very explorable game

263
00:11:05,566 --> 00:11:07,308
just through the perspective of the camera.

264
00:11:08,477 --> 00:11:11,657
So you can start to once again break down exploration

265
00:11:11,737 --> 00:11:14,258
into sub-archetypes and start to look at how the camera

266
00:11:14,278 --> 00:11:15,498
provides new opportunities.

267
00:11:16,138 --> 00:11:17,639
It's more than just big spaces.

268
00:11:17,779 --> 00:11:19,899
There's little puzzles that we can put all through the level

269
00:11:19,959 --> 00:11:21,980
now that we can aim the camera in different perspectives.

270
00:11:22,920 --> 00:11:24,780
We have optional fights that you can opt into.

271
00:11:24,840 --> 00:11:26,141
Those are just great because they give you

272
00:11:26,161 --> 00:11:27,181
a bit of player autonomy.

273
00:11:27,981 --> 00:11:30,222
And finally, this level actually connects to the game's hub,

274
00:11:30,262 --> 00:11:31,222
which is the Lake of Nine,

275
00:11:31,242 --> 00:11:32,602
and we'll go into that a little bit later,

276
00:11:32,622 --> 00:11:34,643
but it's a larger sort of discussion

277
00:11:34,683 --> 00:11:37,123
about how exploration on level-to-level flow works.

278
00:11:38,403 --> 00:11:40,845
So once again, you can see that exploration

279
00:11:40,885 --> 00:11:42,607
is pretty heavily represented in this level.

280
00:11:42,647 --> 00:11:44,348
Of course, it does bunch up a little bit

281
00:11:44,428 --> 00:11:46,770
in the most explorable space,

282
00:11:46,870 --> 00:11:51,133
which is the mason's mini hub right in front of his head.

283
00:11:51,633 --> 00:11:53,414
But also, if you look at the back end of the level,

284
00:11:53,735 --> 00:11:55,296
it's more than just building big spaces.

285
00:11:55,376 --> 00:11:57,637
We want you to seek out nooks and crannies in every room,

286
00:11:57,818 --> 00:11:59,979
even if it's a more linear space or a load hallway.

287
00:12:00,239 --> 00:12:02,261
We want to fill that full of secrets, lore,

288
00:12:02,361 --> 00:12:04,322
additional moments, and so forth.

289
00:12:05,383 --> 00:12:06,864
So when you put it all together,

290
00:12:07,866 --> 00:12:11,631
I think you have a level that accurately delivers on the three pillars, combat, narrative and

291
00:12:11,671 --> 00:12:12,312
exploration.

292
00:12:13,153 --> 00:12:17,499
And if you use these correctly, you can achieve the variety and pacing that I think we're

293
00:12:17,519 --> 00:12:20,823
looking to master, a mix of action and adventure.

294
00:12:22,248 --> 00:12:24,809
The stonemason level is sort of what you might call one of

295
00:12:24,829 --> 00:12:27,311
the more level designer-y levels as well.

296
00:12:27,391 --> 00:12:28,571
It's particularly good at this.

297
00:12:28,651 --> 00:12:31,133
And it's not a full vertical slice, and we don't treat

298
00:12:31,193 --> 00:12:33,054
every level like a template or anything like that.

299
00:12:33,514 --> 00:12:36,256
But it was a particularly good level to get online early in

300
00:12:36,276 --> 00:12:38,377
the project, because it really did prove to us that if you

301
00:12:38,417 --> 00:12:40,758
mix and match these three pillars together, you can get

302
00:12:40,798 --> 00:12:43,099
a lot of versatility, and you can get a lot of variety.

303
00:12:43,820 --> 00:12:45,501
And this is, in essence, why I believe in

304
00:12:45,541 --> 00:12:46,441
core pillars so much.

305
00:12:47,455 --> 00:12:51,396
When you go to design spaces, front of mind for all designers

306
00:12:51,416 --> 00:12:53,517
should really be, how do I use these?

307
00:12:54,017 --> 00:12:55,117
How do I mix and match them?

308
00:12:55,537 --> 00:12:57,958
How do I start to think about them to create a lot of focus?

309
00:12:58,418 --> 00:12:59,979
And if you do this, you'll end up

310
00:13:00,019 --> 00:13:03,240
with a level that feels, a game that feels very different

311
00:13:03,300 --> 00:13:05,940
from level to level, but still feels consistent

312
00:13:06,020 --> 00:13:08,041
from the overall level to level experience.

313
00:13:08,741 --> 00:13:11,402
So with that in mind, we'll add rule number one to our deck.

314
00:13:12,605 --> 00:13:16,207
And we can start to look into our next most important technique,

315
00:13:16,247 --> 00:13:19,248
which is converting these pillars into recognizable metrics.

316
00:13:19,868 --> 00:13:21,308
And that's where rule number two comes in.

317
00:13:22,309 --> 00:13:24,289
Early on in the project, we had to make a decision

318
00:13:24,329 --> 00:13:26,910
about what type of construction of this game we wanted to use.

319
00:13:27,470 --> 00:13:30,631
And we made the decision that we were going to be a very metrics-focused game.

320
00:13:31,512 --> 00:13:33,893
So we can start to think, how do our core pillars

321
00:13:33,993 --> 00:13:36,794
and our metrics come together to help us architect spaces?

322
00:13:37,514 --> 00:13:39,194
A lot of people talk about design metrics.

323
00:13:40,015 --> 00:13:40,755
What does it even mean?

324
00:13:41,255 --> 00:13:41,895
Quick definition.

325
00:13:42,795 --> 00:13:46,377
I like to think of metrics as just a design measurement

326
00:13:46,658 --> 00:13:47,958
that communicates gameplay.

327
00:13:48,259 --> 00:13:49,499
If used correctly, you should start

328
00:13:49,519 --> 00:13:51,080
to build a rhythm in your head as to what

329
00:13:51,100 --> 00:13:52,201
the different measurements mean.

330
00:13:53,221 --> 00:13:54,702
And all games have this.

331
00:13:55,163 --> 00:13:58,645
If you're playing Tomb Raider, maybe jump heights and jump

332
00:13:58,665 --> 00:14:00,286
widths might be super important.

333
00:14:00,786 --> 00:14:03,607
Playing a racing game might be about width server.

334
00:14:04,348 --> 00:14:08,169
paths or where we go on-road, off-road, all these types of things,

335
00:14:08,629 --> 00:14:10,750
really important for what type of game you're making.

336
00:14:11,330 --> 00:14:13,451
So of course the first question you should be asking is,

337
00:14:13,991 --> 00:14:17,952
how do we make metrics that emphasize and accentuate the core pillars of the game?

338
00:14:19,033 --> 00:14:22,274
Our task is to determine metrics that are most important

339
00:14:22,634 --> 00:14:25,235
for highlighting and promoting the goals of the game.

340
00:14:26,575 --> 00:14:26,715
So...

341
00:14:28,622 --> 00:14:31,523
With that in mind, you can start to quickly route your head,

342
00:14:31,783 --> 00:14:33,424
once again, through the core pillars of the game.

343
00:14:34,044 --> 00:14:36,925
At a simplest level, well, for metrics for combat,

344
00:14:37,605 --> 00:14:39,666
we don't want snags or frustrations.

345
00:14:39,866 --> 00:14:42,368
OK, how do we create a metric that creates that?

346
00:14:42,968 --> 00:14:45,169
For narrative, sure, it's easy enough

347
00:14:45,209 --> 00:14:46,870
to say we want no camera cuts.

348
00:14:46,890 --> 00:14:49,511
But how do we actually create a metric to deliver on that goal?

349
00:14:50,451 --> 00:14:53,033
And for exploration, this is a game without a jump button.

350
00:14:53,594 --> 00:14:55,015
When you're looking around the environments,

351
00:14:55,055 --> 00:14:58,178
how do we create more explorable spaces while also allowing

352
00:14:58,198 --> 00:14:59,739
you to scan the horizon and start

353
00:14:59,779 --> 00:15:01,480
to get a quick snapshot in the back of your head

354
00:15:01,520 --> 00:15:02,902
as to what those metrics might mean?

355
00:15:03,402 --> 00:15:05,404
If you get to a dead end and it doesn't actually

356
00:15:05,484 --> 00:15:07,345
reward exploration, you're going to be bummed out,

357
00:15:07,606 --> 00:15:08,947
not going to want to explore anymore, right?

358
00:15:09,307 --> 00:15:11,649
So those metrics start to put a lot of psychology in your head.

359
00:15:13,904 --> 00:15:16,786
This here is one of our most important team documents.

360
00:15:16,866 --> 00:15:18,267
It's called the Level Building Codes,

361
00:15:18,347 --> 00:15:20,769
and it was created by Michael Chang and James Riding.

362
00:15:21,349 --> 00:15:23,751
And it details all the metrics out in meters.

363
00:15:24,332 --> 00:15:26,253
You can see here that Kratos, he mostly

364
00:15:26,334 --> 00:15:28,295
uses one meters, two meters, and three meters.

365
00:15:28,355 --> 00:15:31,217
And we try to really stick to those values

366
00:15:31,298 --> 00:15:34,100
as much as possible, even in more organic spaces.

367
00:15:34,580 --> 00:15:37,162
You can see that he has five meters as kind of his drop-off

368
00:15:37,222 --> 00:15:38,143
heights and so forth.

369
00:15:38,944 --> 00:15:40,684
And as we start to get more complicated,

370
00:15:40,824 --> 00:15:43,465
all the different vaults and squeezes and wall presses,

371
00:15:43,645 --> 00:15:46,266
all these things have very clearly laid out metrics.

372
00:15:47,406 --> 00:15:50,367
So if done correctly, the visual archetypes are established

373
00:15:50,887 --> 00:15:52,028
and layouts remain clear.

374
00:15:53,808 --> 00:15:54,949
Once you're happy with the metrics,

375
00:15:55,229 --> 00:15:57,530
they go into a test bed and you can examine them further.

376
00:15:58,030 --> 00:15:59,030
Here's a quick example.

377
00:15:59,470 --> 00:16:01,951
As he runs through, keep an eye on the three meters

378
00:16:02,071 --> 00:16:03,232
and we'll come back to that in a moment.

379
00:16:11,147 --> 00:16:12,428
So it's pretty straightforward stuff.

380
00:16:12,508 --> 00:16:14,210
You can see everything's nicely laid out.

381
00:16:15,211 --> 00:16:17,193
It's easy to test that the animations are going to line

382
00:16:17,233 --> 00:16:17,693
up correctly.

383
00:16:17,713 --> 00:16:21,297
And boom, there's our 3 meter one right in front of us.

384
00:16:21,798 --> 00:16:24,761
Let's take a closer look at the 3 meter.

385
00:16:24,861 --> 00:16:27,103
3 meter boost is, I love this one.

386
00:16:27,263 --> 00:16:29,846
It's really simple because it's a vault that Kratos can

387
00:16:29,886 --> 00:16:31,448
do to get to an upper ledge.

388
00:16:32,922 --> 00:16:40,847
It's not so high that you might feel like you're going to move to the next space or trigger the next cinematic or move on to a big fight or anything like that.

389
00:16:41,167 --> 00:16:44,109
But it is just high enough that it removes you from the planar space.

390
00:16:44,789 --> 00:16:46,170
And it's perpendicular.

391
00:16:46,570 --> 00:16:48,652
It's a very strong, sharp edge.

392
00:16:49,132 --> 00:16:50,833
And it's roughly at Kratos' eye level.

393
00:16:51,053 --> 00:16:52,374
So the 3-meter boost is great.

394
00:16:52,594 --> 00:16:55,356
It can be used to separate the combat space a little bit.

395
00:16:55,456 --> 00:16:57,277
It can be used to reward a secret.

396
00:16:58,218 --> 00:17:01,140
And if used correctly, it starts to build a rhythm in your head

397
00:17:01,180 --> 00:17:03,522
as to what the role of the three meter boost may be.

398
00:17:03,542 --> 00:17:05,284
There's a lot of other archetypes.

399
00:17:05,344 --> 00:17:08,006
This is why people call metrics sometimes level Legos

400
00:17:08,206 --> 00:17:09,107
or similar like that.

401
00:17:09,507 --> 00:17:10,908
Because when combined together, they

402
00:17:10,948 --> 00:17:13,730
make a very traditional BSP layout, or sheet layout,

403
00:17:13,850 --> 00:17:14,391
as we call it.

404
00:17:15,632 --> 00:17:17,553
This is the stonemason level early on.

405
00:17:18,154 --> 00:17:21,396
And you can see that these metrics were very early attempts

406
00:17:21,496 --> 00:17:23,858
to start to see how these level rules may

407
00:17:23,918 --> 00:17:24,719
start to come together.

408
00:17:25,720 --> 00:17:28,221
Over here, you can see that there's some early attempts

409
00:17:28,261 --> 00:17:31,041
to get combat spaces and combat metrics laid out correctly.

410
00:17:31,741 --> 00:17:34,022
Up the top, you can see early examples of vaults.

411
00:17:34,562 --> 00:17:35,642
And down on the bottom right,

412
00:17:35,682 --> 00:17:37,423
you can see that these are some early attempts

413
00:17:37,463 --> 00:17:39,023
to start working out what these climb metrics

414
00:17:39,063 --> 00:17:40,503
and climb animations might look like.

415
00:17:41,263 --> 00:17:42,644
As we get further into development,

416
00:17:42,784 --> 00:17:44,424
these metrics were actually pretty successful,

417
00:17:44,864 --> 00:17:46,764
and so we started to look into more advanced ones.

418
00:17:48,165 --> 00:17:51,045
Over here, you can see that we added little jump gaps.

419
00:17:51,365 --> 00:17:52,705
This is maybe a little bit more rhythm

420
00:17:52,765 --> 00:17:54,946
that we can start to build into the nav metrics.

421
00:17:55,859 --> 00:17:58,160
The environment artist told us that slopes

422
00:17:58,320 --> 00:17:59,940
was something that was super important to them

423
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:01,781
based on their research of the Nordics.

424
00:18:02,181 --> 00:18:04,242
So we started to look into what IK heights would be

425
00:18:04,262 --> 00:18:05,802
and how we could build with those in mind.

426
00:18:06,342 --> 00:18:07,983
And finally, a point of pride for me

427
00:18:08,003 --> 00:18:09,623
is you'll see over on the right-hand side

428
00:18:09,963 --> 00:18:12,224
that initial metric that we created for the fight space

429
00:18:12,244 --> 00:18:13,644
has actually retained its design.

430
00:18:13,945 --> 00:18:16,765
And even as it got a more sort of detailed pass,

431
00:18:16,865 --> 00:18:18,206
it's actually held its structure.

432
00:18:18,906 --> 00:18:20,327
That's spot on.

433
00:18:20,367 --> 00:18:22,327
This is the value of laying it out correctly.

434
00:18:23,531 --> 00:18:25,793
So when you step through the stonemason level,

435
00:18:25,833 --> 00:18:27,575
you'll see there's a really basic core path.

436
00:18:28,035 --> 00:18:29,977
And now we can start to think, once again,

437
00:18:30,217 --> 00:18:31,638
how will these metrics come together

438
00:18:31,678 --> 00:18:34,020
to make combat, narrative, and exploration?

439
00:18:34,701 --> 00:18:36,102
Here's our three combat spaces.

440
00:18:36,562 --> 00:18:38,544
You can see there is a more wide linear space

441
00:18:38,584 --> 00:18:39,385
at the front of the level.

442
00:18:40,125 --> 00:18:45,412
Up the back, we've got a more traditional arena scenario that takes place at the head where we can increase intensity.

443
00:18:45,892 --> 00:18:55,003
And then actually, on the back right there, you'll see that this was a space that we also laid out to be another arena, which is a bit too similar back to back, right?

444
00:18:55,243 --> 00:18:58,687
So we had to introduce a character there to spice it up and make it a bit more interesting.

445
00:19:00,194 --> 00:19:01,435
In terms of the narrative pillar,

446
00:19:01,956 --> 00:19:04,158
you'll see that the Mason himself is pretty much

447
00:19:04,218 --> 00:19:05,379
a perfect narrative setup.

448
00:19:05,439 --> 00:19:07,922
It's a fallen giant whose last breath

449
00:19:07,942 --> 00:19:09,783
has frozen the entire world around him.

450
00:19:10,124 --> 00:19:10,924
It's a great setup.

451
00:19:11,385 --> 00:19:12,546
But despite what you may think, we

452
00:19:12,566 --> 00:19:14,027
don't know every line of dialogue

453
00:19:14,067 --> 00:19:16,590
or every piece of narrative that is written

454
00:19:16,610 --> 00:19:17,811
at the start of the project, right?

455
00:19:18,412 --> 00:19:24,676
So what we try to do is lay out the space so that there's tons of opportunity for banter or environmental storytelling or set pieces in general.

456
00:19:25,077 --> 00:19:30,501
And that means that the writers can come in at different phases in the project and still make interesting moments between the characters.

457
00:19:31,801 --> 00:19:33,762
And finally, up the back there, this

458
00:19:33,802 --> 00:19:35,303
is one of the cinematic transitions.

459
00:19:35,503 --> 00:19:37,444
This is a very early attempt to try and work out

460
00:19:37,524 --> 00:19:38,905
how we were actually going to funnel you

461
00:19:38,925 --> 00:19:41,727
from gameplay into cinematics with no camera cuts.

462
00:19:42,167 --> 00:19:43,888
In this example, Kratos uses a climb.

463
00:19:44,228 --> 00:19:46,049
And that's a great way to limit his movements

464
00:19:46,069 --> 00:19:48,511
so that we can start to create blends between gameplay

465
00:19:48,911 --> 00:19:49,571
and cinematics.

466
00:19:50,439 --> 00:19:53,240
And in terms of exploration, you can actually see here,

467
00:19:53,280 --> 00:19:55,180
this is where I showed you the jump gaps earlier.

468
00:19:55,460 --> 00:19:56,880
This was kind of a failed experiment,

469
00:19:56,940 --> 00:19:58,401
even though the level designer, Kai Zheng,

470
00:19:58,421 --> 00:20:00,321
did an incredible job of this level.

471
00:20:01,281 --> 00:20:03,062
Actually, we found out that if you are a game

472
00:20:03,102 --> 00:20:05,082
without a jump button, it is just not that fun

473
00:20:05,222 --> 00:20:07,002
to move around and lean into the nav.

474
00:20:07,462 --> 00:20:09,003
So later on, we actually swapped these out

475
00:20:09,043 --> 00:20:11,303
with little bonus puzzles that involved throwing the axe,

476
00:20:11,503 --> 00:20:13,404
which we thought was a bit more in tune

477
00:20:13,424 --> 00:20:16,044
with the game's strengths rather than maybe its limitations.

478
00:20:16,724 --> 00:20:17,885
So once you string it all together,

479
00:20:18,841 --> 00:20:21,764
you have a layout that can actually fit all in Maya,

480
00:20:22,104 --> 00:20:24,447
which is great, because we don't have camera cuts

481
00:20:24,487 --> 00:20:26,629
in this game, so it's really important

482
00:20:26,649 --> 00:20:28,371
that we can actually fit it all in one scene,

483
00:20:28,791 --> 00:20:29,852
and it's great for workflow.

484
00:20:30,701 --> 00:20:35,182
So you can probably tell from how much I am going into this

485
00:20:35,802 --> 00:20:37,743
that I am really proud of how the level designer,

486
00:20:37,783 --> 00:20:38,783
Kai, did with this.

487
00:20:39,284 --> 00:20:40,924
If you strip away the production of the level,

488
00:20:41,404 --> 00:20:44,005
there is a lot of really simple rules that make up this space.

489
00:20:44,045 --> 00:20:46,366
They are not super fancy, and they are not super complicated.

490
00:20:46,646 --> 00:20:48,306
They are just a lot of repeatable metrics

491
00:20:48,386 --> 00:20:50,067
and repeatable pieces that come together

492
00:20:50,087 --> 00:20:51,107
to make an overall layout.

493
00:20:52,007 --> 00:20:54,268
And ultimately, it is the core pillars

494
00:20:54,468 --> 00:20:56,849
and those initial metrics that are the first building blocks

495
00:20:56,889 --> 00:20:57,829
of level construction.

496
00:20:59,250 --> 00:21:00,391
If you know your core pillars,

497
00:21:00,792 --> 00:21:02,533
and you have a generally clear layout,

498
00:21:02,733 --> 00:21:04,135
I believe you'll have a strong canvas

499
00:21:04,175 --> 00:21:05,916
for more complicated decisions, right?

500
00:21:06,257 --> 00:21:07,838
And if you do the groundwork to do that,

501
00:21:07,898 --> 00:21:09,860
you can start to take on more complex things,

502
00:21:09,980 --> 00:21:13,283
like variety, pacing, mixing it up, all these things.

503
00:21:13,923 --> 00:21:15,465
Which brings us to our next set of rules,

504
00:21:16,346 --> 00:21:17,106
achieving variety.

505
00:21:17,126 --> 00:21:17,166
So,

506
00:21:19,618 --> 00:21:24,502
I mentioned a lot that we're always looking for the mix of action and adventure, right?

507
00:21:24,522 --> 00:21:30,006
Never leaning too hard into making the action fatiguing and never leaning too softly into

508
00:21:30,026 --> 00:21:31,047
the adventuring elements.

509
00:21:31,708 --> 00:21:36,291
And since the game's been out for a while now, we do hear from players that they feel

510
00:21:36,311 --> 00:21:39,914
like it has a good mix of scenarios, including combat, narrative, and exploration.

511
00:21:40,634 --> 00:21:41,214
Which is awesome.

512
00:21:41,714 --> 00:21:42,975
I'm really glad to hear that.

513
00:21:43,035 --> 00:21:44,655
And you never know until the game ships, right?

514
00:21:44,695 --> 00:21:47,476
So when you hear that, you're very relieved in some ways.

515
00:21:48,796 --> 00:21:50,957
And also, players often tell us that they

516
00:21:50,977 --> 00:21:53,618
feel like it keeps moving from a moment-to-moment perspective,

517
00:21:53,658 --> 00:21:54,478
that it stays fresh.

518
00:21:55,038 --> 00:21:56,939
So with that in mind, I want to detail two rules

519
00:21:56,959 --> 00:21:59,039
that I think are really important for achieving variety.

520
00:22:00,080 --> 00:22:04,021
The first is that all levels sort of promote or sell

521
00:22:04,081 --> 00:22:05,841
a major theme throughout the level.

522
00:22:05,901 --> 00:22:08,422
I'm fond of saying good levels have a strong theme.

523
00:22:09,389 --> 00:22:13,031
So put simply, to create a theme or variety,

524
00:22:13,591 --> 00:22:15,812
there has to be some kind of unique gameplay element,

525
00:22:15,912 --> 00:22:19,214
something that acts as a start point or an inception,

526
00:22:19,494 --> 00:22:21,215
maybe like a nucleus for an idea.

527
00:22:21,235 --> 00:22:23,736
And our hope is that that will give us

528
00:22:23,916 --> 00:22:26,437
a breadth of different scenarios that we can create.

529
00:22:27,578 --> 00:22:29,339
And once that unique gameplay element

530
00:22:29,399 --> 00:22:31,680
or that unique level toy or whatever you wanna call it

531
00:22:31,700 --> 00:22:32,660
has been established,

532
00:22:33,461 --> 00:22:35,241
it sort of becomes an anchor for the level.

533
00:22:36,271 --> 00:22:38,112
If you establish it correctly in the level

534
00:22:38,152 --> 00:22:40,614
and you teach it correctly, then we can be confident

535
00:22:40,874 --> 00:22:43,276
that we can start throwing more complex scenarios

536
00:22:43,316 --> 00:22:44,997
at the player and more complexity

537
00:22:45,398 --> 00:22:47,759
and more variety at the player through the course of the level.

538
00:22:48,640 --> 00:22:50,661
And once you've got enough of these scenarios strung together,

539
00:22:51,502 --> 00:22:52,583
you've got a theme, right?

540
00:22:53,123 --> 00:22:55,525
So that brings us to our second rule.

541
00:22:56,045 --> 00:22:58,807
All critical path levels unlock a new ability.

542
00:23:00,228 --> 00:23:02,110
Put simply, these are distributed

543
00:23:02,130 --> 00:23:03,371
about every 90 to 120 minutes or so.

544
00:23:05,997 --> 00:23:08,618
And as above, these are the unique gameplay elements

545
00:23:08,638 --> 00:23:10,138
that drive the theme throughout the level.

546
00:23:10,938 --> 00:23:12,859
Most importantly, since a new one's unlocked

547
00:23:12,959 --> 00:23:15,300
every 90 to 120 minutes, it helps the level

548
00:23:15,340 --> 00:23:17,220
to make it feel different from the one before it,

549
00:23:17,501 --> 00:23:19,701
and it helps the level to make it feel different

550
00:23:19,721 --> 00:23:20,582
from the one after it.

551
00:23:20,602 --> 00:23:21,942
It's a lot of good variety.

552
00:23:22,002 --> 00:23:23,783
It prevents a lot of blandness, right,

553
00:23:23,803 --> 00:23:25,483
which is always a little bit of the fear.

554
00:23:25,603 --> 00:23:27,744
Making bland levels is not great.

555
00:23:28,404 --> 00:23:30,805
So, you pair these two rules together, you've got a basic flow.

556
00:23:31,366 --> 00:23:36,208
Every level unlocks a new ability, and then we can use that ability to drive a theme throughout

557
00:23:36,248 --> 00:23:36,568
the level.

558
00:23:38,889 --> 00:23:42,391
And once we know our unique ability, the level designer can sort of go hog-wild.

559
00:23:42,411 --> 00:23:47,334
We can start to think about how this mechanic will work with combat, narrative, and exploration.

560
00:23:48,223 --> 00:23:49,784
If it's a really great mechanic, it

561
00:23:49,884 --> 00:23:51,465
should be able to talk to all three

562
00:23:51,505 --> 00:23:54,267
of the most important elements of the game.

563
00:23:54,368 --> 00:23:56,609
Personal favorite of mine is the hook shot.

564
00:23:56,789 --> 00:23:57,850
Everyone loves the hook shot.

565
00:23:58,150 --> 00:23:59,231
You can use it to navigate.

566
00:23:59,331 --> 00:24:00,192
You can use it to fight.

567
00:24:00,252 --> 00:24:01,413
You can grab rupees with it.

568
00:24:01,433 --> 00:24:02,494
You can solve puzzles with it.

569
00:24:02,814 --> 00:24:04,615
The hook shot literally talks to everything

570
00:24:04,675 --> 00:24:06,517
in the game that is the most important element.

571
00:24:06,557 --> 00:24:08,798
And that's why it is so meaningful to the player.

572
00:24:09,519 --> 00:24:14,563
And so if paced correctly and the items are meaningful,

573
00:24:14,603 --> 00:24:15,984
then players will actually get excited

574
00:24:16,064 --> 00:24:17,625
and anticipate the next big unlock.

575
00:24:18,550 --> 00:24:21,314
So here is the ability that's utilized in the Stone Mason

576
00:24:21,334 --> 00:24:21,575
level.

577
00:24:22,256 --> 00:24:23,297
It's called the Shock Arrow.

578
00:24:24,118 --> 00:24:25,520
And Shock Arrows are super basic.

579
00:24:26,041 --> 00:24:29,225
Shock Arrows are magic arrows that Atreus

580
00:24:29,245 --> 00:24:31,008
can fire at red crystals.

581
00:24:31,749 --> 00:24:32,890
And they go, boom.

582
00:24:33,511 --> 00:24:34,052
That's pretty much it.

583
00:24:34,993 --> 00:24:37,275
But it's actually awesome because its simple design

584
00:24:37,495 --> 00:24:38,896
allows for a lot of versatility.

585
00:24:38,996 --> 00:24:40,718
If it's too complex a level mechanic,

586
00:24:40,998 --> 00:24:42,079
then we're really going to struggle

587
00:24:42,119 --> 00:24:43,180
to create a lot of variety,

588
00:24:43,740 --> 00:24:45,622
or we're going to struggle to have scenarios

589
00:24:45,642 --> 00:24:47,023
where the player might be under duress

590
00:24:47,243 --> 00:24:49,125
and actually be able to use the mechanic.

591
00:24:49,525 --> 00:24:51,527
So its simplicity is actually terrific.

592
00:24:52,047 --> 00:24:54,970
So, of course, before it looks like this in the game,

593
00:24:55,030 --> 00:24:56,331
we do a really basic prototype

594
00:24:56,351 --> 00:24:58,012
to make sure it's actually fun

595
00:24:58,132 --> 00:25:00,434
and that it's going to deliver on this potential versatility

596
00:25:00,454 --> 00:25:00,875
and variety.

597
00:25:01,855 --> 00:25:03,036
And here is the prototype.

598
00:25:58,795 --> 00:26:01,420
So this level prototype was actually created by John Marcello,

599
00:26:01,460 --> 00:26:03,664
who's one of the senior designers at Santa Monica Studio.

600
00:26:04,124 --> 00:26:05,567
We started this project so long ago,

601
00:26:05,627 --> 00:26:07,851
he actually used the touch pad as the prototype.

602
00:26:08,893 --> 00:26:10,856
And everyone thought it generally had potential.

603
00:26:11,582 --> 00:26:14,343
So from there, it went through some additional iterations

604
00:26:14,383 --> 00:26:16,524
to find out what the best controls and rules would be.

605
00:26:16,764 --> 00:26:18,284
We have a whole systems design department

606
00:26:18,304 --> 00:26:20,385
that are really masters of this domain.

607
00:26:20,745 --> 00:26:23,006
And then as level designers, we try to use those mechanics.

608
00:26:24,046 --> 00:26:26,347
But eventually, it was determined

609
00:26:26,387 --> 00:26:29,068
that it would be even cooler if Atreus could help you out.

610
00:26:29,168 --> 00:26:32,109
We might get back a little bit more combat, exploration,

611
00:26:32,449 --> 00:26:32,889
and narrative.

612
00:26:33,009 --> 00:26:35,130
Maybe we can actually get father-son connection out

613
00:26:35,150 --> 00:26:36,130
of this mechanic as well.

614
00:26:36,831 --> 00:26:38,393
So it was added to Atreus's bow.

615
00:26:39,014 --> 00:26:41,958
Basically, you press square, and Atreus fires the arrow for you.

616
00:26:41,978 --> 00:26:44,722
It's pretty simple, but as I mentioned,

617
00:26:45,343 --> 00:26:47,606
our desire is to create father-son connection

618
00:26:47,646 --> 00:26:50,030
and also give the level designers a lot of versatility

619
00:26:50,310 --> 00:26:51,191
in scenario design.

620
00:26:52,245 --> 00:26:54,405
As you can see here, this mechanic is awesome

621
00:26:54,705 --> 00:26:56,606
because it can be used on tons of different stuff.

622
00:26:56,726 --> 00:26:57,706
And the red material,

623
00:26:57,966 --> 00:26:59,646
which does actually have some narrative in the game,

624
00:26:59,686 --> 00:27:02,147
it's kind of the roots of the Yadraz school tree.

625
00:27:02,647 --> 00:27:05,708
So between visual development and the level mechanic team,

626
00:27:06,068 --> 00:27:08,728
and between the level designers and the environment artists,

627
00:27:08,788 --> 00:27:10,769
we're able to create tons of versatility

628
00:27:10,869 --> 00:27:13,009
as to how this red sap or this red material

629
00:27:13,029 --> 00:27:14,030
can be placed around the level.

630
00:27:14,610 --> 00:27:16,510
Spot on, because that's the thing

631
00:27:16,530 --> 00:27:18,771
that's going to allow us to create an established theme

632
00:27:18,871 --> 00:27:19,431
throughout the level.

633
00:27:20,878 --> 00:27:23,439
In addition, it was thought that we had a pretty good mechanic,

634
00:27:23,539 --> 00:27:26,400
but that we could get a bit of additional play out of it,

635
00:27:26,540 --> 00:27:27,981
once again, to push variety.

636
00:27:28,341 --> 00:27:30,961
So there was the decision made to add a throwable element,

637
00:27:31,042 --> 00:27:31,902
which is awesome.

638
00:27:32,302 --> 00:27:33,822
Now we can have static scenarios,

639
00:27:34,102 --> 00:27:36,723
and we can have scenarios that allow a bit more player

640
00:27:36,763 --> 00:27:37,263
creativity.

641
00:27:39,488 --> 00:27:42,230
And finally, once we're really happy with it,

642
00:27:42,290 --> 00:27:44,392
late in development, we polish it

643
00:27:44,412 --> 00:27:46,113
so that it can accentuate its role

644
00:27:46,273 --> 00:27:49,275
and be a very prominent theme throughout the level.

645
00:27:49,675 --> 00:27:51,396
You can see here that it has an inner glow

646
00:27:51,696 --> 00:27:54,338
so that it pops just a little bit more, tiny bit arcadey.

647
00:27:54,798 --> 00:27:56,800
And you can also see that as you pass the camera

648
00:27:56,880 --> 00:27:59,241
around this object, it has a little bit of sheen on it

649
00:27:59,261 --> 00:28:01,583
so that it's likely to just catch your eye

650
00:28:01,683 --> 00:28:02,603
as you move the camera.

651
00:28:04,605 --> 00:28:08,667
So let's take a look at one of the scenarios in the level

652
00:28:09,387 --> 00:28:11,628
and how it works with the core pillars.

653
00:28:12,048 --> 00:28:14,129
Once again, try to think of this in terms of combat,

654
00:28:14,449 --> 00:28:15,730
narrative, and exploration.

655
00:28:16,490 --> 00:28:17,611
I'll start with narrative here.

656
00:28:18,471 --> 00:28:22,033
This sort of concept of a puzzle is great

657
00:28:22,373 --> 00:28:23,514
for slowing down the player

658
00:28:23,634 --> 00:28:25,655
and just having narrative moments in general.

659
00:28:25,715 --> 00:28:27,075
In fact, maybe after a little while,

660
00:28:27,135 --> 00:28:29,076
the AI partner can even give you a hint.

661
00:28:30,320 --> 00:28:35,124
This scenario is also terrific because it's been fabulously integrated by the environment art team.

662
00:28:35,144 --> 00:28:39,568
It's actually the ring finger of the giant, so it foreshadows the narrative that you're going to see further on.

663
00:28:40,148 --> 00:28:44,732
And you may not know this, but all the runes on the ring were actually translated by someone,

664
00:28:44,752 --> 00:28:48,075
so they all actually have real meaning if you go back and translate them,

665
00:28:48,095 --> 00:28:49,836
if you're really into the narrative of the game.

666
00:28:51,349 --> 00:28:54,411
So in terms of exploration, well, you can see here

667
00:28:54,431 --> 00:28:56,012
he's blowing up an additional secret,

668
00:28:56,293 --> 00:28:59,135
and that may not be exploration per se, right?

669
00:28:59,175 --> 00:29:01,257
It's not a super explorable space.

670
00:29:01,277 --> 00:29:03,158
He didn't find a hidden dungeon or anything like that.

671
00:29:03,619 --> 00:29:05,100
But really, it's kind of more of a gimme.

672
00:29:05,380 --> 00:29:07,162
It's a tutorial for exploration.

673
00:29:07,222 --> 00:29:09,163
It's teaching you, keep an eye out

674
00:29:09,203 --> 00:29:10,845
for future scenarios like this,

675
00:29:11,105 --> 00:29:14,528
and keep your brain checked for shock crystals,

676
00:29:14,828 --> 00:29:18,211
because shock crystals can equal secrets, right?

677
00:29:18,331 --> 00:29:18,751
And so...

678
00:29:19,412 --> 00:29:23,053
This is a little bit of a gimme, but it does sort of train you on exploration.

679
00:29:23,953 --> 00:29:27,995
And then finally, for combat, well the shock arrows are really great for combat in general.

680
00:29:28,035 --> 00:29:31,256
That was already thought of because Atreus can actually use them in combat scenarios,

681
00:29:31,296 --> 00:29:33,077
give you an advantage, they have a whole skill tree.

682
00:29:33,577 --> 00:29:38,239
This is where I love this scenario because if you actually fire a shock arrow in combat,

683
00:29:39,252 --> 00:29:42,155
at the ring, you can get an AOE and you can actually blast the AI.

684
00:29:42,615 --> 00:29:46,639
So everything starts to talk to each other and you can even sort of experiment with it

685
00:29:46,759 --> 00:29:47,720
while under duress.

686
00:29:47,940 --> 00:29:49,982
That's part of the advantage of it being so simple.

687
00:29:52,045 --> 00:29:53,426
Now, you may not remember these scenarios.

688
00:29:53,446 --> 00:29:55,528
I actually showed you them at the top of the presentation.

689
00:29:55,628 --> 00:29:57,189
But a lot of the scenarios I showed you

690
00:29:57,249 --> 00:29:59,191
actually had shot crystals in the background.

691
00:29:59,671 --> 00:30:00,312
Let's take a look.

692
00:30:00,972 --> 00:30:04,155
You'll see that this is the first one I showed you,

693
00:30:05,096 --> 00:30:06,317
where it's just in the background.

694
00:30:06,357 --> 00:30:08,799
Maybe it hints to you that you can get a bit of damage

695
00:30:08,859 --> 00:30:09,920
if you're experimental.

696
00:30:10,461 --> 00:30:12,783
You can see that it can be used for throwable puzzles

697
00:30:12,963 --> 00:30:13,724
in the top right.

698
00:30:14,764 --> 00:30:19,366
Down below, it's actually used for a shot crystal chandelier section.

699
00:30:19,886 --> 00:30:23,328
And the thing that's sort of nice about the shot crystals is even though they are kind of big and glowy,

700
00:30:23,368 --> 00:30:25,509
we're able to get them into a lot of the environments.

701
00:30:25,969 --> 00:30:30,831
So they can even be in the background of cinematics without being like too offensive or anything like that.

702
00:30:31,451 --> 00:30:33,352
Let's take a look at it from a top-down perspective.

703
00:30:34,292 --> 00:30:38,134
Once again, you'll see that the shock arrows are really nicely distributed throughout the level.

704
00:30:38,574 --> 00:30:41,876
And I love that, because that is the thing that is making it a theme.

705
00:30:42,456 --> 00:30:46,198
Some players even called it the shock arrow level when they would come at a playtest,

706
00:30:46,218 --> 00:30:48,559
which if you're a level designer is the real compliment, right?

707
00:30:48,599 --> 00:30:50,840
When they ignore everything else and just talk about the mechanics.

708
00:30:53,905 --> 00:30:55,988
And it was also great from a production perspective and

709
00:30:56,028 --> 00:30:58,772
a code perspective because as I mentioned at the top of the presentation,

710
00:30:58,812 --> 00:31:00,334
we can't code every feature ever.

711
00:31:00,474 --> 00:31:03,658
We're in a very fortunate situation to have so much support from Sony.

712
00:31:04,058 --> 00:31:07,263
But even still, we have limitations and we don't want to code everything ever.

713
00:31:07,523 --> 00:31:11,168
So using the shock arrow is still a very efficient use of the mechanic as well.

714
00:31:12,380 --> 00:31:15,864
So you can probably tell from my pride and joy with all these scenarios that I think

715
00:31:15,884 --> 00:31:18,546
the level designer, Kai, absolutely crushed it.

716
00:31:18,787 --> 00:31:21,129
I think this is one of the best themes throughout the game.

717
00:31:21,449 --> 00:31:23,091
This is what I love about level design.

718
00:31:23,771 --> 00:31:25,213
And he really nailed the flow.

719
00:31:25,573 --> 00:31:30,678
Level unlocks a key item, and then the level uses that item to create a strong theme throughout

720
00:31:30,718 --> 00:31:30,998
the level.

721
00:31:31,884 --> 00:31:33,825
But there is an additional detail to this.

722
00:31:34,385 --> 00:31:37,587
As I alluded to, every level unlocks a key item, right?

723
00:31:38,167 --> 00:31:41,169
And that starts to touch on how we think about more of the

724
00:31:41,209 --> 00:31:43,031
level-to-level experience and what the

725
00:31:43,191 --> 00:31:44,491
overarching experience is.

726
00:31:45,272 --> 00:31:47,754
So with that in mind, the next rule is all

727
00:31:47,774 --> 00:31:49,335
about creating a format.

728
00:31:51,096 --> 00:31:51,856
What is a format?

729
00:31:51,896 --> 00:31:55,118
Some people talk about format maybe like structure or

730
00:31:55,478 --> 00:31:55,939
something like that.

731
00:31:57,011 --> 00:31:59,192
I like to define it as the intuitive rules

732
00:31:59,252 --> 00:32:01,333
by which levels flow into one another.

733
00:32:02,214 --> 00:32:04,255
So, if the pieces are lined up correctly,

734
00:32:04,455 --> 00:32:07,436
you can start to create some psychology and a mental layer,

735
00:32:07,897 --> 00:32:09,558
and players can start to identify

736
00:32:09,618 --> 00:32:11,539
with how they'll engage in sessions

737
00:32:11,639 --> 00:32:12,699
and how they'll play levels.

738
00:32:13,520 --> 00:32:16,201
In God of War, there's actually a lot of different types of content.

739
00:32:16,281 --> 00:32:19,723
There's critical path levels, there's exploration levels,

740
00:32:20,303 --> 00:32:22,524
even little puzzles that are optional.

741
00:32:22,964 --> 00:32:25,446
There's actually entire areas you can discover on your own.

742
00:32:26,370 --> 00:32:29,736
So it's really important that we start to build some expectations in the player's head.

743
00:32:30,717 --> 00:32:34,744
If you enter a story mission in a game, how do you know intuitively that you're going

744
00:32:34,764 --> 00:32:38,050
to maybe start like 60 minutes worth of content and start to get into it?

745
00:32:39,213 --> 00:32:42,035
there's some psychology and consistency within the game

746
00:32:42,055 --> 00:32:43,736
to start establishing that rhythm in your head.

747
00:32:44,356 --> 00:32:46,818
And if you go down a side path and you think to yourself,

748
00:32:46,918 --> 00:32:48,759
oh, awesome, here I go, down this little side path,

749
00:32:48,799 --> 00:32:49,960
