not just because I matched the colors.

1003
00:43:33,342 --> 00:43:35,224
And remember before, our level-to-level flow,

1004
00:43:35,824 --> 00:43:37,346
you know, establish a theme.

1005
00:43:38,208 --> 00:43:41,090
hit a key turning point, earn a new ability or item,

1006
00:43:42,491 --> 00:43:45,393
get a clear exploration break, continue, continue, continue.

1007
00:43:46,594 --> 00:43:49,135
Let's run this against the stonemason level.

1008
00:43:49,976 --> 00:43:52,278
In the previous level, the player goes up to the mountains,

1009
00:43:52,858 --> 00:43:54,779
and they use the previous level's mechanic,

1010
00:43:54,860 --> 00:43:56,301
which in this case,

1011
00:43:56,481 --> 00:43:58,642
let's just call it orange to avoid spoilers.

1012
00:44:00,764 --> 00:44:01,724
And they start to use this.

1013
00:44:01,884 --> 00:44:03,566
It also creates a theme throughout the level.

1014
00:44:03,606 --> 00:44:04,907
They hit a capitulation point,

1015
00:44:04,987 --> 00:44:06,528
and they are rewarded with the shock arrow

1016
00:44:06,668 --> 00:44:07,368
at the end of this level.

1017
00:44:08,228 --> 00:44:10,250
The player can now make their way back to the hub.

1018
00:44:10,530 --> 00:44:13,312
Having confidently been taught how to use the shock arrow,

1019
00:44:13,332 --> 00:44:15,434
they can now choose to explore with it if they want.

1020
00:44:16,234 --> 00:44:17,075
And then when they're ready,

1021
00:44:17,835 --> 00:44:20,237
they can explore back for a quick narrative beat.

1022
00:44:20,277 --> 00:44:22,419
There's a sort of mini mission that takes place here,

1023
00:44:22,459 --> 00:44:22,979
a mini level.

1024
00:44:23,339 --> 00:44:25,461
And when they're ready to go to the main critical path level,

1025
00:44:25,701 --> 00:44:27,322
they head back to the stonemason level.

1026
00:44:27,763 --> 00:44:30,284
We drive that theme all the way through the level,

1027
00:44:30,385 --> 00:44:32,166
create a lot of variety, a lot more pacing,

1028
00:44:32,526 --> 00:44:33,887
increase the complexity a little bit

1029
00:44:34,007 --> 00:44:35,228
of the shock arrow scenarios.

1030
00:44:35,788 --> 00:44:38,450
Boom, just as you're getting fatigued, key turning point,

1031
00:44:38,791 --> 00:44:41,132
new ability or item, teach you three scenarios,

1032
00:44:41,593 --> 00:44:42,873
and then you're back to the hub.

1033
00:44:44,475 --> 00:44:46,016
And as we strip all of this away,

1034
00:44:46,096 --> 00:44:49,818
it becomes apparent that this layout is very similar

1035
00:44:49,918 --> 00:44:50,939
to the big wagon wheel.

1036
00:44:51,700 --> 00:44:53,581
Overall, I believe the Lake of Nine

1037
00:44:53,741 --> 00:44:55,963
was great at delivering the goals of a hub.

1038
00:44:56,403 --> 00:44:59,265
And it's this hub design that, in turn,

1039
00:44:59,365 --> 00:45:01,246
is really successful at achieving

1040
00:45:01,306 --> 00:45:03,568
the sort of Metroidvania element that people often

1041
00:45:03,908 --> 00:45:05,029
enjoy in this game.

1042
00:45:06,147 --> 00:45:08,012
So there's your hope.

1043
00:45:09,255 --> 00:45:11,221
And with that, we're back to our rule slide.

1044
00:45:11,261 --> 00:45:12,103
I'll add it to the annex.

1045
00:45:13,484 --> 00:45:15,446
Let's go through all of these, and I'll quickly recap.

1046
00:45:16,026 --> 00:45:18,628
It's also a good time to mention that these are actually

1047
00:45:19,229 --> 00:45:21,570
sometimes really good design priorities.

1048
00:45:21,650 --> 00:45:24,713
As you step through a really big project or a lot of work,

1049
00:45:25,954 --> 00:45:27,315
you can also start to think of these

1050
00:45:27,395 --> 00:45:29,757
as maybe the order of operations that you might want to take

1051
00:45:29,857 --> 00:45:31,198
experiences on in a game.

1052
00:45:31,698 --> 00:45:34,040
Up front is just about how we start to think together

1053
00:45:34,100 --> 00:45:36,362
and how we work together to start creating some focus

1054
00:45:36,562 --> 00:45:39,784
as a design group, whether that's technically designers

1055
00:45:39,824 --> 00:45:41,366
or just people who we work with.

1056
00:45:42,326 --> 00:45:47,811
Rule number two represents our desire to represent those core pillars as metrics. How are we going to construct?

1057
00:45:48,251 --> 00:45:55,758
Effectively and consistently amongst one another rules three and four it's all about the backbone of creativity and the backbone of variety and pacing

1058
00:45:56,198 --> 00:46:03,004
Rule five ensures that we have clear exploration breaks and and that levels flow clearly from one another and finally our newest rule number six

1059
00:46:03,144 --> 00:46:09,189
It's sort of an overarching wrapper or an overarching layout for the whole experience and with that we have a game

1060
00:46:10,387 --> 00:46:12,848
But since it's GDC, and since we're

1061
00:46:12,868 --> 00:46:15,550
here to learn about the tricky nature of development,

1062
00:46:15,610 --> 00:46:16,891
I'll now step back through all of these

1063
00:46:16,931 --> 00:46:17,851
and show you where they all broke.

1064
00:46:20,793 --> 00:46:22,774
And not just because there was bad design,

1065
00:46:22,814 --> 00:46:24,155
or not just because something was wrong.

1066
00:46:24,476 --> 00:46:26,777
Sometimes it's also an opportunity.

1067
00:46:27,057 --> 00:46:30,299
Sometimes maybe a problem just didn't work out

1068
00:46:30,339 --> 00:46:33,121
the way we expected, or sometimes it's just common sense.

1069
00:46:33,601 --> 00:46:35,463
So here's rule number one.

1070
00:46:36,478 --> 00:46:39,681
What you might have noticed is that this game has a lot of puzzles,

1071
00:46:40,201 --> 00:46:44,043
and puzzles are not represented anywhere in the core pillars of the game.

1072
00:46:44,724 --> 00:46:45,324
So what's the deal?

1073
00:46:45,825 --> 00:46:47,786
Are puzzles a core pillar or not, right?

1074
00:46:48,186 --> 00:46:50,788
And this is a question that took us about four and a half years to work out.

1075
00:46:52,287 --> 00:46:54,128
So even though the puzzles take a lot of work,

1076
00:46:54,188 --> 00:46:56,168
and even though they do take a lot of play testing,

1077
00:46:56,268 --> 00:46:57,969
they're a great addition to the game

1078
00:46:58,429 --> 00:47:01,289
because they let us tap into the three pillars of the game

1079
00:47:01,709 --> 00:47:02,630
in really great ways.

1080
00:47:03,410 --> 00:47:05,690
I like to look at the puzzles in terms of sort of

1081
00:47:06,650 --> 00:47:08,071
emphasizers or subcategories

1082
00:47:08,311 --> 00:47:10,031
of combat narrative and exploration.

1083
00:47:10,531 --> 00:47:11,432
As I mentioned earlier,

1084
00:47:11,532 --> 00:47:12,992
puzzles are great for just slowing down

1085
00:47:13,012 --> 00:47:13,912
the action in general,

1086
00:47:13,952 --> 00:47:16,093
so we can get a lot of narrative between the characters.

1087
00:47:17,833 --> 00:47:20,054
There's a lot more father-son teamwork in a puzzle,

1088
00:47:20,134 --> 00:47:21,994
so that can be a good way to emphasize that pillar.

1089
00:47:23,015 --> 00:47:26,257
In terms of exploration, puzzles often make us rethink the space,

1090
00:47:26,277 --> 00:47:28,078
so they keep us in the space a little bit longer.

1091
00:47:28,599 --> 00:47:32,141
At Santa Monica Studios, we truly do have some of the best environment artists in the world,

1092
00:47:32,161 --> 00:47:36,244
so we're always looking for ways to get the player to soak in the space just a little bit more

1093
00:47:36,625 --> 00:47:39,226
and try to appreciate the spaces, not blow through them too quickly.

1094
00:47:39,967 --> 00:47:42,729
And finally, for combat, the puzzles actually teach you to learn.

1095
00:47:42,889 --> 00:47:44,390
I'll show you one more time this scenario.

1096
00:47:45,649 --> 00:47:47,651
This one is early in the game, and it's actually

1097
00:47:47,711 --> 00:47:48,973
tuned a little bit difficult.

1098
00:47:49,453 --> 00:47:49,754
Why?

1099
00:47:50,454 --> 00:47:52,797
Because we would rather that you fail on the scenario

1100
00:47:52,817 --> 00:47:55,860
a couple of times and learn how to throw the axe more

1101
00:47:55,901 --> 00:47:57,482
effectively, so that when you step

1102
00:47:57,542 --> 00:47:59,404
into the more complex scenarios in the game,

1103
00:47:59,805 --> 00:48:01,487
you have trained yourself how to do something that

1104
00:48:01,947 --> 00:48:03,709
doesn't really exist in any other game.

1105
00:48:03,849 --> 00:48:06,092
Throwing an axe and recalling it is fairly abstract.

1106
00:48:06,152 --> 00:48:07,593
It's something that makes this game unique.

1107
00:48:08,094 --> 00:48:10,416
And so by tuning this puzzle just a bit difficult,

1108
00:48:10,456 --> 00:48:13,880
we can be guaranteed that the types of players

1109
00:48:13,920 --> 00:48:17,944
who will engage with stretch content or more complex content

1110
00:48:17,964 --> 00:48:20,427
are also the types of players who might train and master.

1111
00:48:21,628 --> 00:48:22,809
more complex mechanics.

1112
00:48:23,169 --> 00:48:24,589
So in short, puzzles are a big part of the game,

1113
00:48:24,609 --> 00:48:25,370
but they're not a core pillar.

1114
00:48:26,610 --> 00:48:28,451
Number two, we are a metrics-based game.

1115
00:48:29,212 --> 00:48:32,193
So the Norse landscape itself is really organic

1116
00:48:32,253 --> 00:48:34,134
and really mysterious, and that was one thing

1117
00:48:34,154 --> 00:48:36,175
that was very obvious to us from day one.

1118
00:48:37,076 --> 00:48:39,036
But metrics are actually really rigid,

1119
00:48:39,357 --> 00:48:40,377
and they're deliberately so.

1120
00:48:40,497 --> 00:48:43,539
So how do you kind of tie these things together?

1121
00:48:43,619 --> 00:48:45,460
There's a natural conflict that emerges, right?

1122
00:48:46,120 --> 00:48:47,781
So here's a quick example of where it broke.

1123
00:48:48,613 --> 00:48:50,314
I've shown you my favorite example, which

1124
00:48:50,374 --> 00:48:51,375
is the 3-meter boost.

1125
00:48:51,896 --> 00:48:53,357
And on the right-hand side, you can

1126
00:48:53,397 --> 00:48:55,038
see that there's a lot of debris or shrub.

1127
00:48:55,599 --> 00:48:58,001
So in the test bed, it looks great.

1128
00:48:58,421 --> 00:49:01,303
You can see that it's a very clear perpendicular object.

1129
00:49:01,384 --> 00:49:02,885
It's kind of turreted in this example,

1130
00:49:02,925 --> 00:49:04,446
so we can accentuate the nature of it.

1131
00:49:04,947 --> 00:49:06,588
But by the time we put debris over it,

1132
00:49:06,668 --> 00:49:09,931
it sort of loses its ability to be an architectural piece.

1133
00:49:11,810 --> 00:49:12,150
What now?

1134
00:49:12,590 --> 00:49:13,210
What are we going to do?

1135
00:49:13,430 --> 00:49:14,991
Get mad at each other, blame each other,

1136
00:49:15,251 --> 00:49:17,532
scream at each other, go into each other's files,

1137
00:49:17,592 --> 00:49:18,073
pull out shrubs?

1138
00:49:18,293 --> 00:49:18,553
No.

1139
00:49:19,573 --> 00:49:21,634
What we actually did is come up with a style guide.

1140
00:49:22,114 --> 00:49:23,835
This indicates where shrubs and debris

1141
00:49:23,855 --> 00:49:27,577
should actually be placed and where design metrics need

1142
00:49:27,597 --> 00:49:30,198
to be kept important to keep things clear.

1143
00:49:31,199 --> 00:49:32,860
Fortunately, we have an environment team

1144
00:49:32,880 --> 00:49:35,002
who is extraordinarily talented and very

1145
00:49:35,062 --> 00:49:36,163
passionate about the game.

1146
00:49:36,663 --> 00:49:38,965
And you might think that pitching to a team, hey,

1147
00:49:38,985 --> 00:49:41,167
we're going to talk about rules for shrub placement

1148
00:49:41,207 --> 00:49:44,229
or where shrubs can't go might be the most boring conversation

1149
00:49:44,329 --> 00:49:44,469
ever.

1150
00:49:44,489 --> 00:49:46,510
But actually, everyone really rallied together

1151
00:49:46,550 --> 00:49:48,832
to talk about how we could create a style guide

1152
00:49:48,872 --> 00:49:49,333
for shrubs.

1153
00:49:49,773 --> 00:49:51,955
And the net result is that shrubs and debris

1154
00:49:51,995 --> 00:49:54,356
can actually be used not only to, uh,

1155
00:49:58,732 --> 00:50:01,134
When they're removed, they not only make spaces very clear,

1156
00:50:01,434 --> 00:50:02,835
but if you put them in certain places,

1157
00:50:02,855 --> 00:50:04,817
they can actually act as a deterrent as well.

1158
00:50:05,117 --> 00:50:07,679
So by creating these two style guide rules,

1159
00:50:08,039 --> 00:50:14,283
we could actually basically create organic placement,

1160
00:50:14,424 --> 00:50:15,905
where we didn't want you to go,

1161
00:50:16,345 --> 00:50:17,526
and architectural placement,

1162
00:50:17,566 --> 00:50:19,087
where we wanted to emphasize you going.

1163
00:50:19,507 --> 00:50:21,669
So there's a lot of positive and negative

1164
00:50:21,849 --> 00:50:23,770
visual expectations that you can actually create.

1165
00:50:25,188 --> 00:50:27,529
Also, what about rules 3 and 4?

1166
00:50:27,569 --> 00:50:28,029
Variety.

1167
00:50:28,109 --> 00:50:29,250
All levels have a theme, right?

1168
00:50:30,050 --> 00:50:31,750
Not in the back 25% of this game.

1169
00:50:32,030 --> 00:50:33,551
I'm not going to spoil anything for you,

1170
00:50:33,651 --> 00:50:35,231
but the reason is twofold.

1171
00:50:35,571 --> 00:50:36,111
What's the deal?

1172
00:50:36,171 --> 00:50:37,712
Did you run out of money again?

1173
00:50:37,812 --> 00:50:38,912
Did you run out of ideas?

1174
00:50:38,972 --> 00:50:40,833
Was four years too long to make a game?

1175
00:50:40,853 --> 00:50:42,713
Do you not want to go to five or six?

1176
00:50:42,853 --> 00:50:42,973
No.

1177
00:50:43,494 --> 00:50:45,497
We don't have an unlimited budget on features,

1178
00:50:45,677 --> 00:50:48,301
and we do try to use them as effectively as possible.

1179
00:50:48,461 --> 00:50:50,284
And when we started to paper plan the game,

1180
00:50:50,724 --> 00:50:52,687
we did realize that we were going to run out of mechanics

1181
00:50:52,707 --> 00:50:54,309
and that we didn't have an unlimited budget

1182
00:50:54,330 --> 00:50:57,534
and that we didn't want to spend forever just prototyping

1183
00:50:57,594 --> 00:50:57,975
and whatever.

1184
00:50:58,655 --> 00:51:01,956
The back part of the game are really more about mastery

1185
00:51:02,196 --> 00:51:03,056
than about newness.

1186
00:51:04,256 --> 00:51:07,617
Keep in mind all of the level theming that I mentioned earlier,

1187
00:51:07,977 --> 00:51:10,778
it's not specifically about creating new items all the time,

1188
00:51:10,838 --> 00:51:11,978
it's about creating variety.

1189
00:51:12,538 --> 00:51:14,198
There is more ways to create variety

1190
00:51:14,258 --> 00:51:16,118
than just adding more mechanics to the game.

1191
00:51:16,839 --> 00:51:17,759
Here's a quick example.

1192
00:51:18,579 --> 00:51:21,219
The Temple Flip level towards the end of the game is often,

1193
00:51:21,299 --> 00:51:23,200
oops, sorry, let me get that up for you.

1194
00:51:29,765 --> 00:51:30,465
Oh no.

1195
00:51:32,867 --> 00:51:34,508
Well, the Tempo Flip level of the game

1196
00:51:34,628 --> 00:51:37,030
is actually often described as final exam.

1197
00:51:38,111 --> 00:51:39,652
And what that means is that it uses

1198
00:51:39,872 --> 00:51:42,554
all the previous level mechanics of the game together.

1199
00:51:43,815 --> 00:51:46,958
And so let me get this back up and running.

1200
00:51:47,038 --> 00:51:48,018
I think we crashed.

1201
00:51:50,480 --> 00:51:51,301
Oh, there we go.

1202
00:51:51,321 --> 00:51:51,361
OK.

1203
00:51:56,597 --> 00:51:59,278
So in this example, it's the only time in the game

1204
00:51:59,618 --> 00:52:02,479
where Crusher Trap and Shock Arrow are used together.

1205
00:52:02,860 --> 00:52:06,141
The reason for this is that the Crusher Trap is a one-hit KO.

1206
00:52:06,681 --> 00:52:08,902
And so when we combine these two things together,

1207
00:52:09,282 --> 00:52:11,543
there is a different emotion and more variety

1208
00:52:11,743 --> 00:52:13,504
established through the combination of those two

1209
00:52:13,564 --> 00:52:13,904
elements.

1210
00:52:14,524 --> 00:52:16,225
So the deeper the player gets into the game,

1211
00:52:16,545 --> 00:52:17,785
the more they know about the game,

1212
00:52:17,825 --> 00:52:20,386
and the more you can promote challenge, strategy,

1213
00:52:20,506 --> 00:52:22,327
and metagaming through the existing mechanics.

1214
00:52:22,767 --> 00:52:25,048
And the net result is still interesting gameplay, right?

1215
00:52:25,088 --> 00:52:25,908
It's still variety.

1216
00:52:27,573 --> 00:52:29,796
Finally, I'll keep this one really quick.

1217
00:52:30,536 --> 00:52:32,138
Once we had good level-to-level flow,

1218
00:52:32,298 --> 00:52:34,560
players were still not really understanding,

1219
00:52:34,620 --> 00:52:36,682
or certain players were still not really understanding where

1220
00:52:36,702 --> 00:52:38,104
they could and couldn't explore.

1221
00:52:38,865 --> 00:52:40,887
And we believed pretty strongly from a level design

1222
00:52:40,927 --> 00:52:42,668
perspective that the hub was the right way to go,

1223
00:52:42,688 --> 00:52:44,010
that we'd done all the right work,

1224
00:52:44,030 --> 00:52:45,771
and that we'd created a good, overarching format.

1225
00:52:46,252 --> 00:52:47,453
But some players just really needed

1226
00:52:47,473 --> 00:52:49,655
to be hit over the head that they could explore.

1227
00:52:49,695 --> 00:52:51,117
They needed that final confirmation.

1228
00:52:51,737 --> 00:52:53,758
So to solve this, we collaborated with the writers

1229
00:52:54,519 --> 00:52:56,640
so that whenever the player re-enters the hub,

1230
00:52:56,920 --> 00:52:58,961
they're given an additional line of dialogue

1231
00:52:59,281 --> 00:53:01,542
from Kratos and Atreus, indicating that it

1232
00:53:01,582 --> 00:53:02,923
might be a good time to explore.

1233
00:53:03,883 --> 00:53:06,484
You can actually see here that whenever they step

1234
00:53:06,504 --> 00:53:09,146
through these two doors, they'll get a little line of dialogue,

1235
00:53:09,166 --> 00:53:11,487
and they'll say something like, hey, maybe we

1236
00:53:11,507 --> 00:53:13,148
should go exploring right now.

1237
00:53:13,248 --> 00:53:13,968
What do you think, Dad?

1238
00:53:14,528 --> 00:53:15,249
But the thing is.

1239
00:53:16,315 --> 00:53:18,757
We had to write them so many times so that it was never

1240
00:53:18,957 --> 00:53:20,398
mandating the player to do so.

1241
00:53:20,778 --> 00:53:22,259
And so with some of these things,

1242
00:53:22,379 --> 00:53:24,581
it really does come down to play testing and trying

1243
00:53:24,621 --> 00:53:26,582
a variety of different lines and trying

1244
00:53:26,602 --> 00:53:28,404
a different group of reads.

1245
00:53:29,885 --> 00:53:31,886
Finally, hubs are not open worlds.

1246
00:53:32,166 --> 00:53:34,588
Well, one interesting conflict here

1247
00:53:34,848 --> 00:53:37,410
is whether we needed to align too much to the purity

1248
00:53:37,530 --> 00:53:38,811
of a wheel-spoke format.

1249
00:53:38,831 --> 00:53:40,693
Let's take a look at it one more time.

1250
00:53:40,733 --> 00:53:43,395
You can see here that the hub-spoke is a literal circle.

1251
00:53:44,948 --> 00:53:45,969
which is great on paper.

